result.execSummary:
The defendant Alan J Nagle was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Knowingly Violate a Domestic Abuse Order - Injunction, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 813.12(8)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

From Dr Thompson re: Def's medical condition.

9:03 AM - Def in court.  Tim Gruenke appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Gruenke: no agmt. Def told me that he wants a short con't into November. He is currently in pain from an assault that happened at his house and needs to have surgeries and he has a civil trial in October in Winona. CRT: he talked to Andrea yesterday. DEF: I have a doc appt today right after. CRT: by Wed of next week, describing the med situation and the need for a delay, I will grant the request for a con't. 
JS: 11/23
JT: 11/24

Mr. Nagle called me to state that he is having surgery tomorrow and would not make it to court for the final pre-trial.  He said his house was broken into over the weekend and he was assaulted with a shovel.  I spoke with Judge Horne and he agreed to taking the hearing off but would require Mr. Nagle to submit medical documents.  Mr. Nagle then said he wanted to keep the hearing on and would get a taxi from MN to the courthouse.  Mr. Nagle stated he might have difficulties getting into the courthouse (will need a wheelchair), got upset and then hung up on me.
Jury trial on September 15, 2015 at 08:45 am.
